      <hedline>
        <hl1>Staying in Iraq, and Getting Out</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arthur L Yeager letter suggests dividing Iraq into three separate and distinct nations as prelude to American withdrawal, rather than forcing warring factions to co-exist (Nov 27 Nicholas D Kristof Op-Ed article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Nicholas D. Kristof rightly argues that any abrupt American withdrawal would result in a bloody civil war.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Nicholas D. Kristof rightly argues that any abrupt American withdrawal would result in a bloody civil war.</p>
        <p>Rather than trying to force the disparate factions to coexist, new lines should be drawn to divide Iraq into three separate and distinct nations: a Kurdish state in the north, a Shiite land in the south and a Sunni nation west of Baghdad.</p>
        <p>The Kurds would retain their autonomy within their own borders; independent Shiites could govern without concern for a Sunni uprising; and as a separate country, the Sunnis would no longer fear reprisal.</p>
        <p>Only then will the objective of a free, peaceful and productive Iraq be achieved.</p>
        <p>Arthur L. Yeager  Edison, N.J., Nov. 27, 2004</p>
      </block>
